---
import LightLayout from '../../../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="Script · GitHub" description="Structured script by blocks for Stripe Product Sense.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 pb-6">
    <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Back to hub</a>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mt-6 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">🐙</span>
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black !my-0" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Script · GitHub</h1>
        <p class="!my-1 font-medium" style="color: var(--color-primary);">~7 min · B2B + developer infrastructure (closest to Stripe)</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="prose-factory">

      <div class="card !p-5 my-6" style="background: rgba(236,72,153,0.10); border: 1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.25);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">📌 How to use this script</h3>
        <p class="!mb-0">GitHub is the product closest to Stripe's domain (developer infrastructure). The strong piece is <strong>"the PR as the atomic unit of communication between developers on the internet"</strong>. That sentence differentiates you.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[USER]</h2>
      <p>"I'm going to talk about <strong>GitHub</strong>, which I use daily. My primary user is <strong>the professional developer in a team of 5 to 50 people</strong>, not the solo dev or the open source maintainer."</p>
      <p>"I choose this segment because it sustains GitHub's business: Enterprise and Teams plans, enough complexity to need Actions, Codespaces, Copilot Business, but still individual agency in technical decisions. Other segments: the student learning, the open source maintainer, the 500+ enterprise team. I'll touch on as contrast."</p>

      <h2>[SUB-SEGMENTS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>The committer.</strong> Maintains code, opens PRs, runs CI. For them GitHub is a daily workflow tool."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The reviewer.</strong> Spends more time on others' PRs than on their own commits. Tech leads, staff engineers. For them GitHub is a governance interface."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The orchestrator.</strong> Configures Actions, manages repo settings, integrates external tools. For them GitHub is an automation platform."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"I'm going to focus on <strong>the reviewer</strong>, because it's the sub-segment where GitHub has the deepest moat and where a product change has asymmetric returns for Enterprise."</p>

      <h2>[ECOSYSTEM]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Git hosting</strong>, competing with GitLab, Bitbucket, self-hosted Gitea, and now AI-first platforms like Cursor."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Developer infrastructure</strong>, competing with CircleCI, Jenkins, Vercel, Netlify, while at the same time being infrastructure for all of them via Actions."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Open source community</strong>, where GitHub doesn't compete, it's structural. GitHub is where modern OSS lives, and that's an asset that can't be replicated."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Adjacent AI coding</strong>, where GitHub via Copilot competes with Cursor, Replit, Lovable, Tabnine, while simultaneously being the training-data source for all of them."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"One extra layer that matters: GitHub has been part of Microsoft since 2018. Any proposal has to think about the relationship with Azure, with OpenAI (partly Microsoft), and with the corporate AI strategy."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 3 with corporate strategic layer. This separates you from the candidate who only knows GitHub as a product, without the Microsoft context.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[THE ATOMIC UNIT]</h2>
      <p>"Before I propose anything, one observation: <strong>the PR is the atomic unit of communication between developers on the internet</strong>. It isn't code, it isn't chat, it isn't a ticket. It's a structured conversation anchored to a concrete code change, with an immutable history, asynchronous, and indexable. That product decision, taken 15 years ago, is what turned GitHub into infrastructure."</p>
      <p>"My proposal builds on that primitive: <strong>when you think about improving GitHub for developers in teams, you think about improving the PR</strong>, not about adding adjacent features."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Anchor sentence. Repeat it. "Atomic unit of communication" is the kind of framing the interviewer will remember.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[PROPOSAL]</h2>
      <p>"My proposal: <strong>persistent AI context per PR</strong>. When you open a PR, GitHub should deliver to the reviewer a Copilot-generated summary including: what the PR changes functionally (not file by file, but behaviour), which parts of the code are critical for humans to review versus boilerplate, and what risks it detects based on repo history."</p>
      <p>"It connects to the reviewer (my sub-segment) directly: their number-one problem is <strong>review time</strong>. A senior reviewer spends 30 to 50% of their week on PRs. If GitHub can reduce that by a third, the value delivered by the platform goes up exponentially. And it reinforces GitHub's AI moat against Cursor: Cursor helps you write code, GitHub helps you review the code others write."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Patterns 5 + 3 combined. The proposal serves the chosen sub-segment AND positions against the adjacent competitor. Double lever.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[EDGE CASES]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, AI summary false positives. If Copilot says 'this is boilerplate' and it actually had a critical bug, the reviewer loses trust. Solution: the summary explicitly marks confidence per section, and team leads configure thresholds."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, sensitive proprietary code that the organisation doesn't want sent to AI inference. Solution: on-premise mode / Copilot Enterprise with a dedicated model, not public API."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, generational dependency. Junior devs who learn to review PRs by reading the AI summary without ever looking directly at the code never develop their own judgement. Mitigation: the AI summary doesn't replace the diff, it precedes it; the diff remains the primary document."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[RISKS: TIGER + PAPER TIGER]</h2>
      <p>"<strong>🐅 Tiger:</strong> inference cost. Generating AI summaries per PR is expensive at scale (GitHub processes millions of PRs per day). Mitigation: tiering by plan (Free doesn't include it, Teams does), aggressive caching, and smaller specialised models, not generic GPT-4."</p>
      <p>"<strong>📰 Paper Tiger:</strong> 'Cursor is going to eat GitHub in developer tools'. Looks plausible but doesn't hold. Cursor competes at the moment of writing code (IDE). GitHub competes at the moment of reviewing, integrating, deploying. Two different products at two different moments in the cycle. The professional developer uses both. The 'replacement' narrative comes from confusing IDE with code-governance platform."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 The Paper Tiger against Cursor is the most relevant move for Stripe, which also lives in developer infrastructure. It's the sentence that will sound familiar and click with the interviewer.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[METRICS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Target:</strong> average review time per PR in teams with the feature active. Measures direct value to the reviewer."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Leading:</strong> summary adoption rate by reviewers in the first 14 days. Target 70%."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Lagging:</strong> Copilot Business retention at 12 months in teams with the feature. Target +10pp over baseline."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Guard rail:</strong> production bug ratio for PRs reviewed with the feature vs without. Cannot rise more than 5% relative. If it does, the AI summary is replacing human review instead of complementing it, and we need to recalibrate."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[TRANSPLANT]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'OK, now do it for developers with less than 10 years of experience who are learning to collaborate on code for the first time'."</p>
      <p>"<strong>OK, let me pause. This changes a lot.</strong>"</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, I assumed review experience as existing capability. For a junior dev learning, the problem isn't 'how long does it take me to review', it's 'what should I look at in a PR?'. A senior-style AI summary doesn't serve them, it would be patronising. I have to rethink this as an educational tool, not a shortcut."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, I assumed professional context with delivery pressure. For a junior learning, the pressure is to learn well, not to deliver fast. The product has to value depth of understanding, not speed."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, I assumed organisational infrastructure (Copilot Business, private repos, configured CI). For a junior dev on personal or academic projects, all of that varies."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"With those assumptions broken, my proposal changes. Instead of 'AI summary', I'd propose <strong>a learning mode where the PR is enriched with pedagogical annotations</strong>. When the junior opens someone else's PR, GitHub suggests questions an experienced reviewer would ask ('what happens if X is null?', 'does this test cover Y?'), not answers. The ontological difference is <strong>from a productivity feature to a didactic feature</strong>, and that changes the whole design."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 The "productive vs didactic" distinction is the strongest piece. It shows you understand that two sub-segments don't need the same feature in a scaled version, they need two different products.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[IF THEY PUSH BACK]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'but if the AI reviews for me, aren't I delegating responsibility? Isn't that problematic for production?'"</p>
      <p>"Good question. Let me distinguish two things. <strong>Delegation of judgement</strong>, where the AI decides whether to merge or not, is problematic and my proposal doesn't do that. <strong>Acceleration of comprehension</strong>, where the AI helps you understand faster what changed, still leaves the decision with the human reviewer. My proposal lives in the second mode. If I wanted it to live in the first, I'd have to design very different guardrails, require explicit human approvals depending on the sensitivity of each change. But that's a different product."</p>

      <hr class="my-10" />

      <div class="card !p-6 my-8" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">🎯 The three anchor sentences</h3>
        <ol class="!mb-0">
          <li><strong>"The PR is the atomic unit of communication between developers on the internet."</strong></li>
          <li><strong>"Cursor competes at the moment of writing; GitHub competes at the moment of reviewing."</strong></li>
          <li><strong>"Acceleration of comprehension, not delegation of judgement."</strong></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-3 mt-10">
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/steam" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Steam</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Hub</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/whatsapp" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">WhatsApp →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</LightLayout>
